Q83:
When people have a Fixed Mindset, they avoid challenging problems because they believe it shows that they are dumb or unintelligent. This simply isn't true. By switching to a Growth Mindset, and believing that one's intelligence can grow over time, people's intelligence actually increases. They attempt difficult problems and ask for help if they get stuck -- this allows them to learn how to do more difficult problems and their intelligence level increases!

At the beginning of first year I was horrible at all of my classes; I didn't understand chemistry, math, or biology. By asking my professors and TAs questions, I gained a deeper understanding of the material and learned how to approach different questions. By the end of the semester I had grown so much and knew so much more, and this was reflected in my grades. If I believed that my intelligence was stagnant I would have avoided practicing what I found hard and I wouldn't have improved. Believing that your intelligence is fixed is a self-fulfilling prophecy. If you believe that you can improve your intelligence -- if you have a Growth Mindset, you will work harder and become smarter.

How do you expect to learn new math skills if you don't make a few mistakes along the way? With a Growth Mindset, you are never thinking about mistakes and instead are eager to learn which takes the stress off of making a mistake. Some stress can be good to get your brain to work harder, but stress constantly from making a mistake is unhealthy for your brain and can damage it. The goal to learn should not be about marks, it should be about mastering the topic at hand. We live in a society that deems marks as the ultimate result to demonstrate the performance of a student, but their are limitations to this. Majority of students just want the marks so they study a type of problem and when a similar problem is on the exam, they know how to approach it. However, if they were asked to solve it again after some time, they don't recall it because they were blindly memorizing the steps to the solution, they didn't really know how to solve it. So the Fixed Mindset may help you pass some obstacles in your way and increase your self-esteem, however, the Growth Mindset is more healthier for your brain, you will master the topic you learn, and you will never have to worry that you weren't smart enough, rather you are continuing to achieve the status of mastering the topic.
Q89: Always put in hard work and practice. There is no harm in practicing really hard for something that you want to learn. Hard work and practice is not only about how many times you read the textbooks and did the questions. It also means did you really want to learn the material or did you just want to memorize it and use it for the exam. Never stop practicing hard questions. The reason these questions are hard is because you haven't mastered them like addition and subtraction yet. Even these topics at first took you probably a very long time, but then you got the hang of it and now you can probably do them faster than a calculator. Finally, asking questions is crucial to your growth. People with the Growth Mindset do well in the long term because they ask so many questions. I know many teachers who used to call out a student in my high school because he/she asked a "dumb" question. The student will feel insulted and will stop learning right there. No new questions are fueling their curiosity and their knowledge will not grow.

Q83:
No part of us is static. Just like how our body grows and changes as we get older, our personality, our views, and our brains do as well. One way of learning is getting taught something - we memorize a certain process, or try to understand a certain concept. But no one will be able to understand everything on their first try, and so making mistakes is also part of the process of learning. When you make mistakes, you can analyze them and think about how to improve. We can all learn from mistakes, and in fact understand the material in more depth since we see so many more cases where things go right or wrong.

So maybe you don't understand certain things now, but if you muster up the courage to try new things and accept that you might fail at first, you'll actually learn and improve. If you adopt a Growth Mindset, in that our brain actually grows and changes with everything we experience, you can improve and do better. The more mistakes you make, the more you will understand and your brain will consequently grow in that area.

Q83: It is important for you to have a Growth Mindset rather than a Fixed Mindset.  A Fixed Mindset is kind of a narrow-minded way of approaching your learning.  Instead of getting discouraged when you can't solve a problem, it is important to try to look at it as a learning opportunity as opposed to an indication of poor intelligence.  Think about why you are unable to solve the problem.  Try to approach it from a new angle.  If you can't solve it still, seek help from a teacher or another student.  Chances are that someone else in the class has the same question as you and will also benefit from you asking questions.  Have an open, Growth Mindset about your learning.  Approach difficult problems as a challenge instead of avoiding them.  Although it may seem difficult and frustrating at first, in the long run you will learn faster and develop better strategies for learning and figuring out things that you don't immediately understand.

Q74: The environment that surrounds us is subconsciously making our brains grow. When we are in an active environment learning is constant - from picking up new skills to getting along with peers we are forced to learn these things and learn them fast in order to "fit in". The people who go through constant learning become "smarter"  in the sense that they get better at learning new things. Scientists used a brain scanner to compare the brains of some people who learned a new skill and some who didn't and found that when humans learn challenging things, your brain cells grow. When your brain cells grow, you become 'smarter'.  So, as the saying goes, "How do you get better? Practice, practice, and more practice!"
Q83:
Hey :)  I can relate to how you are feeling about school right now and I know it's tough but we can get through this! Do you feel like you have lost your motivation to spend your time on schoolwork or to ask for help because you feel like you're not smart enough for anything you do to make a big difference? First, let me tell you that you ARE enough. I can relate to how you are feeling about school right now. I want you to know that you are uniquely YOU and you bring value to this world that no one else can. 
This is just a temporary roadblock within our minds that we need to discuss and come to terms with. What we have is called a Fixed Mindset - when we make mistakes we feel stupid and try to avoid harder problems that we feel we can't solve, we especially avoid challenging problems when working around people who we feel are smarter than us because we believe it will make us 'look stupid'. What we fail to see when we are so caught up in the moment is that our mindset is what determines how we feel and how we view and handle situations. 
What's very important when you have a Fixed Mindset is to see your situation in a new like by adopting a growth mindset. Instead of avoiding our mistakes we must look at them carefully because it will make us smarter. Instead of getting discouraged when faced with challenges because we think we are bad at it, we must spend time to figure out what we do not understand. Be curious and do your research, have a thirst for knowledge and spend time learning about your passion, you can get there. I know you can. All it takes is little steps every day. Work hard and work smart, as long as you work, it will pay off! Believe in yourself and get out there and catch your goals! After all, life is long but it is also really short so make the most of it by learning as much as you can!

Q3:
'-Past midterms: Past examinations are always a good method to test your skills. It can also give you a feel for the structure of the upcoming midterm, which is reassuring.
-Prepare exercise: These exercise are good to check the core concepts thought in computer science. Having trouble with one of these easily pinpoints areas where I should study and practice more.
-Perform exercise: Much like the past midterms, perform exercise can give various examples of the types of questions that might be presented on the midterm.
-Videos on PCRS: These videos goes hand in hand with the prepare exercise, giving core concept explanation on all subjects gone through the term. It is great since it is available to everyone anywhere, so if you misunderstood a certain section, you can easily review it without losing the quality of the explanation, since they come straight from the professors.
-Piazza discussion board: Office hours are difficult to attend with busy schedule. Piazza allows quick answers for questions students have. Especially if they are simple question that require a quick clarification.
-Worksheets: The questions on the midterm is based on information presented in the lectures. So the worksheet are a good review to what the professors will put on the midterm.
-Posted slides: The posted slides and specifically the posted python shell help a lot to go through what professors presented in the lectures.

Q5:
Thursday: go over 1 past midterm, first try all the questions, after trying all, go over the solutions and figure why I didn't get the answer, what concepts I was missing or didn't use, write all those down on separate paper. Solve 2 other midterms, the same way. Study at home, for however long it takes to finish going over 3 old midterms. Between each midterm take 10 minutes break. 
Friday: go over 3 old midterms, same way as yesterday. At library for however long it takes plus 10 minutes breaks.
Saturday: Go over all the concepts I had written done which I had trouble using or remembering to use when solving the 6 old midterms. Go over 3 more old midterms, at home, same timing. 
Sunday: finish with all old midterms. Go over concepts I had trouble with. Go over PCR questions for week 1, 2 ,3 , 4. Go over PCR notes and lecture notes. Re-do worksheets. Mark down any questions from PCR or midterms I had trouble with to go to office hours. At home, same timing. Go to piazza and check questions asked there. 
Monday: go over the midterms, re-do questions I missed on separate page, go over PCR videos notes and lecture notes, at home, for 3-4 hours, with 10 minutes break in between each hour. 
Tuesday: at library go over and re-do PCR questions, go over worksheets and notes, for 3 hours.

Q74: People's intelligence can grow and get better with effort and practice, regardless of 'genetics' because different people's minds are accustomed to different things. But because we are able to learn and adapt by trying new things, our minds can become accustomed to these situations, making us smarter.
Q83: I believe I would tell this friend that closing off our minds to new opportunities prevents character and mental growth. When you have a fixed mindset that, 'No, I can't do this, I'm just not good at this,', it gives you the idea that people's strengths and weaknesses are innate, when really, that usually isn't the case. A professional tennis player is able to reach that level of skill by continuous practice and dedication to his craft. This talent wasn't just in them the moment they were born. Although there may be some genetic or outside factors contributing to possessing a talent, people who are talented at a skill or craft were those that put in the most effort to get there, and this equally applies to being good at a subject. That's why it is important develop a growth mindset in everyday life as it is important to see challenging, new things as opportunities to grow as an individual.

Prepare/perform exercises: It's useful to make sure you know and remember all the course content, as well as getting some practice with it. I can't think of any other ways to use the prepare/perform exercises.

Worksheets: More practice with a skill makes you better at it. I can't think of any other ways to use worksheets besides just doing them.

Fiona has a fixed mindset, so she feels really dumb when she makes mistakes because she thinks that her mistakes must mean she’s not smart at math. Q74: Scientists have been able to collect evidence using brain scans that show a positive association between the size of a person's brain and their participation in learning a new skill, such as juggling. So this suggests that the more we push ourselves to learn new (and hence, difficult) things, our brains will react by growing more so that they can do more work to learn those new skills, knowledge, etc. The brain is like a muscle in this way--it reacts to the stress/challenge of learning by growing.
Q83: There are two kinds of people: those with a FIXED mindset and those with a GROWTH mindset. People with a fixed mindset believe that they are born with a certain level of knowledge and skills and that they are limited by their natural essence. They do not believe that they can grow in different areas of their life through effort and practice. They end up avoiding challenging situations and not putting in the work that is needed to learn and grow. Furthermore, they sabotage their own growth by their own thinking--this is especially obvious when they make mistakes. Rather than learning from their mistakes, they get frustrated and give up because they believe that they have a fixed brain and that they will never learn. Science, on the other hand, has shown that everyone's brain reacts to learning and challenging situations by growing. People with a growth mindset believe in this scientific knowledge that we have the power to grow through deliberate effort and by making mistakes. People with a growth mindset truly believe in their ability to grow and so when they make mistakes, they do not get frustrated--rather, they use those experiences to see what they can learn from it. Furthermore, they are more willing to step outside their comfort zone and seek out more difficult challenges, rather than staying within their comfort zone all the time or doing nothing to grow. Finally, and very importantly, people with a growth mindset are not ashamed to ask for help when they need to. They do not feel embarrassed or shy about their inability to solve problems because they believe that they can grow and overcome those challenges if given the right support and guidance. People with a fixed mindset, on the other hand, will be too embarrassed to ask for help, because of their belief that they possess a fixed set of knowledge and skills that will never increase and that they will expose their lack of knowledge if they ask for help. So, by saying these things, I would try to convince my friend to try to truly adopt a growth mindset!
Q89:
I already believe in the importance of a growth mindset and have been using it to guide how I lead my life. One of the things that I am still working on, however, is trying to adopt alternative learning strategies. Sometimes the best approach to learning is the hard approach, e.g., practicing rewriting our lecture notes in our own words without the aid of any resources, sketching diagrams by hand to explain difficult concepts, and so on. I am working hard to remove bad study habits from my routine so that my study sessions are more effective.

I like how the article broke down the approach to learning using the "formula for growing your brain: effort + good strategies + help from others = brain growth". I think this is a wonderful formula! Thank you for sharing this with us.
Q90:
I think learning math at university has been such a huge challenge in the first year and has really been testing my belief in having a growth mindset. In the first semester especially, I avoided group work and office hours because I always felt underprepared to talk to people about my problems. However, I have changed this semester and am constantly going to office hours and finding study partners so that I have someone to talk to about math and to bounce off ideas. I am continuing to strive and constantly asking for help and advice from profs and senior students about their learning strategies. I am trying to look at math problems from a fresh perspective and developing new habits for doing math rather than continuing old habits picked up from high school. I am trying to practice alternative proof strategies for solving math problems rather than sticking to certain strategies just because they seem easier to me, and constantly making effort to learn new definitions/theorems.

I think if I persist in having the growth mindset and if I keep at it in terms of (i) making the effort; (ii) adopting new and effective learning strategies; and (iii) seeking out help whenever I need it; then I will start seeing positive results soon.

It is important to consciously remind ourselves of the importance of the having a growth mindset because it is easy to fall into the trap of having a fixed mindset when things start becoming tough and stressful.

Q83: Having a fixed mindset can hinder intelligence and prevent you from learning. This is because with a fixed mindset you're less likely to try harder problems and instead stick to the easier ones so as not to fail as you're afraid of feeling stupid if you get an answer wrong. With a fixed mindset, getting a wrong answer can be very discouraging and automatically make you feel like you're bad at the subject you're working on, and that you'll never be good at it. However, by not trying the more challenging questions, you're not putting yourself in a position to learn more and grow or develop new skills for how to go about solving those more challenging problems. But having a growth mindset allows you to take on those more challenging problems with a more open and positive outlook because you know that not getting the right answer to a question doesn't make you stupid, it simply shows you that there is more to be learnt and even gives you the questions that might need to be asked in order to succeed. And by trying harder on these questions, it allows new neural pathways to develop that allow for new skills and strategies to be learnt. Therefore having a growth mindset is much more beneficial to your learning and understanding.

Q90: I honestly don't have much of a fixed mindset from which to draw an example from. I could lie and make one up, but I feel that wouldn't be an honest way to reply, and wouldn't serve us well. But the way I approach obstacles, is to employ two different forms of problem solving. I first exhaust my analytical approaches, and previous knowledge. Then I make an effort to use Gestalt re-imagining of the problem that is causing me difficulty. I do this by considering from a wider perspective and observing it holistically. Then I will shift to observing it though atomizing the problems components down to their simplest operands. By shifting my attention between construal and opacity/transparency I will often find a path to a new approach to solve a problem. If that doesn't work, i'll stop actively attempting to solve it, while maintaining the concept loosely in my mind and infrequently bringing it up in different contexts of my day to see if the lens of my values shifts my attention creating a new salience to the conditions of the problem. But that's just me.

Q83:

Q83: Maybe try thinking about this problem a little differently. Instead of feeling like these concepts being hard for you is a sign of your lack of intelligence, think of your desire to fix them as a sign of your curiosity. I recently learned that the brain is very malleable - it has the capacity to grow quite a bit, for new connections and pathways to be made. But in order to generate these pathways and grow the brain, we have to repeatedly work at things that challenge us. For example, I struggled with Arabic for years until I went to Jordan. Before I went to Jordan, I was afraid to practice speaking because I was afraid of being embarrassed because I would make a lot of mistakes and others would see. In Jordan, every day was forced to practice speaking. I got used to being wrong and didn't take it so personally. Now I can have full conversations with Arabic speakers and my learning is accelerating exponentially because I'm not so hard on myself when I make mistakes - I do not shy away from them anymore because I understand they are part of the learning process.
